Abiodun Nejo, Ado Ekiti legendary broadcaster, Chief Kunle Olasope, is dead. The Efon-Alaaye, Ekiti State born broadcaster, died in Ibadan, the Oyo State capital, on Sunday at the age of 82. Former Secretary-General, Efon Development League, Mr Adeyemi Adejoju, confirmed the death of Olasope, who was until his passage, the chairman, Board of Trustees of the League. He said the late “Olohun Iyo of Africa” served Ekiti and Nigeria to the best of his abilities while he lived. He was indeed a great ambassador in many fronts. Olasope was the first male face and voice on television in Africa when Western Nigeria Television was established in Ibadan by the Western Region Government of Chief Obafemi Awolowo. A community leader,  socialite and a devoted member of St Paul’s Anglican Church, Efon Alaaye, Olasope, who received many awards, was also honoured with the Member of the Order of Niger by the Federal Government. He was the chief press secretary to the then Ogun State governor, Olabisi Onabanjo, between 1979 and 1983. Olasope was also the chairman of Ekiti State Broadcasting Service under former Governor Adeniyi Adebayo. Copyright PUNCH.
